. She recounts how she was entrusted with the publication of Leonard Woolf and Trekkie Ritchie’s love letters; how she found a way to hunt down Charlotte Haldane, one of the first women on Fleet Street; and how she came to write the biography of Max Reinhardt, the man behind the finest English publishing house of the mid-twentieth century.A sharply observant and self-effacing narrator, Adamson brings vividly to life an anglophone upbringing in mid-century Montreal, the London literary scene, and the struggles faced by the women intellectuals of her time. Ghost Stories is a tale of good luck and the hard sleuthing of biographical work before the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBiographerszCanadavBiography. 0aBiography as a literary form. 0aWomen biographerszCanadavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aBodley Head.  aCanadian.  aCharlotte Haldane.  aDawson College Montreal.  aDigital age.  aEnglish.  aGeorge Doreen Rude.  aGraham Greene.  aJBS Haldane.  aLeonard Woolf.  aMary Meigs.  aMax Reinhardt.  aMontreal.  aRay Smith.  aResearching.  aSigrun Bulow-Hube.  aSir George Williams College Montreal.  aTrekkie Ritchie Parsons.  aVincent Brome.  aWomen.  aart craft.  abiography.  acollege teaching.  aearly CEGEP system.  afurniture design.  aintellectuals.  alife writing.  apublisher.  astruggles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228021568?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228021568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228021568/original  a978-3-11-140848-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles